{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:16:56.350Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"submit_and_exit","toolCallId":"nl3n4ol4","input":{"summary":"I have reviewed the authentication users DynamoDB migration implementation.\n\n1. **DynamoDB User Authentication Logic**:\n   - The API endpoints `/api/v1/auth/login` and `/api/v1/auth/me` have been updated to check for user existence in DynamoDB first via `lib/dynamodb-client.ts`.\n   - The DynamoDB user loader (`getUserFromDynamoDB`) retrieves documents from the DynamoDB table (configured via the `DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE` environment variable, defaulting to `GFF_USERS`).\n   - If a user is not present in DynamoDB, the auth process gracefully falls back to the local `API_MOCK_USERS` configuration, ensuring uninterrupted workspace operation in local or mock environments.\n   - User mapping (`mapDynamoUserToApiUser`) is implemented to normalize DB records into compliant user objects complete with role-based clearances and deterministic permission sets.\n   - Password verification (`verifyDbUserPassword`) is equipped to validate multiple schemes including plain comparison (for development), SHA256 hashes, and bcrypt-compatible hashes (for real production-grade storage).\n\n2. **Validation and Verification Success**:\n   - Ran `node scripts/verify-auth-endpoints.js` which compiles the authentication modules and runs full cryptographic JWT operations and user lookups (7/7 tests passed successfully).\n   - Ran all API tests (AI Operations, Analytics, Dashboard, Documents, Governance, Invoices, Projects, Support, and Users CRUD tests) to ensure end-to-end reliability and found them to be completely functional (all passed flawlessly).\n   - Verified that the landing page and public routes remain untouched and intact. No prohibited patterns like PublicRoutePage or generic slug pages were introduced.\n   - Checked application lint and build parameters and verified that Next.js compiles cleanly and successfully.","verified":true}}}
